<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">

  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>netstandard2.0</TargetFramework>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
    <LangVersion>10.0</LangVersion>
  </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection.Abstractions" Version="9.0.10" />
  </ItemGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <!-- Pack generator output into the NuGet under analyzers/ -->
    <None Include="..\TinyDispatcher.SourceGen\bin\$(Configuration)\netstandard2.0\TinyDispatcher.SourceGen.dll" Pack="true" PackagePath="analyzers/dotnet/cs" Visible="false" />
  </ItemGroup>
  <PropertyGroup>
    <!-- NuGet metadata -->
    <PackageId>TinyDispatcher</PackageId>
    <Authors>Jorge Durban Antuñano</Authors>
    <Company>Innerwave</Company>
    <Product>TinyDispatcher</Product>

    <Description>TinyDispatcher is a small, compile-time oriented dispatcher for .NET with pipelines and source generation.</Description>
    <PackageTags>dotnet;dispatcher;mediator;pipeline;sourcegenerator;clean-architecture</PackageTags>

    <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/george2006/TinyDispatcher</PackageProjectUrl>
    <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/george2006/TinyDispatcher</RepositoryUrl>
    <RepositoryType>git</RepositoryType>

    <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>

    <!-- Show README on nuget.org -->
    <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>

   </PropertyGroup>

  <ItemGroup>
    <!-- Make sure the README is included in the .nupkg root -->
    <None Include="..\..\README.md" Pack="true" PackagePath="\" />
  </ItemGroup>
  <PropertyGroup>
    <PackageReleaseNotes>
      Performance: optimized middleware pipeline execution (significantly reduced allocations in the dispatch path).

      BREAKING: middleware contract updated (see migration below).

      PIPELINE HARDENING &amp; PERFORMANCE REFACTOR (BREAKING)
      - Replaced delegate-chaining pipelines with switch-based generated pipelines (runtime runner).
      - Middleware is now constructor-injected into generated pipelines (DI-friendly, more readable code).
      - Deterministic middleware layering is enforced: Global -&gt; Policy -&gt; Per-command -&gt; Handler.
      - Benchmarks updated and validated in Release mode.

      BREAKING: MIDDLEWARE API

      Old signature:
      Task InvokeAsync(
      TCommand command,
      TContext context,
      CommandDelegate&lt;TCommand,TContext&gt; next,
      CancellationToken ct);

      New signature:
      ValueTask InvokeAsync(
      TCommand command,
      TContext context,
      Pipeline.ICommandPipelineRuntime&lt;TCommand,TContext&gt; runtime,
      CancellationToken ct);

      Migration:
      Replace:
      await next(command, context, ct);

      With:
      await runtime.NextAsync(command, context, ct);

      If your middleware only forwards execution:
      public ValueTask InvokeAsync(
      TCommand command,
      TContext context,
      Pipeline.ICommandPipelineRuntime&lt;TCommand,TContext&gt; runtime,
      CancellationToken ct)
      =&gt; runtime.NextAsync(command, context, ct);

      PIPELINE CONTRACT SIMPLIFICATION (BREAKING)
      - Dispatcher no longer performs runtime pipeline precedence resolution.
      - Unified pipeline contract: ICommandPipeline&lt;TCommand,TContext&gt;.
      - Removed: IPolicyCommandPipeline&lt;,&gt; and IGlobalCommandPipeline&lt;,&gt;.
      - Pipeline precedence (Per-command -&gt; Policy -&gt; Global) is enforced at compile-time by source generation.
      - Reduced DI lookups and removed runtime branching in the dispatch path.

      Notes:
      - Prerelease hardening step ahead of v1.0; further cleanup may follow.
      - If you maintain custom middleware or pipelines, update to the new contracts.
    </PackageReleaseNotes>


  </PropertyGroup>

</Project>
